I can explain Hume's position here pretty easily.<br>
<br>
Hume argues that we are born and we have a series of sense perceptions that we begin to associate with various emotions as we develop. Some sense perceptions invariably associate with other sense perceptions. We begin to assume that these have a cause and effect relationship. <br>
<br>
This assumption is normal, but cause and effect are not by any understanding of reason necessary. It is entirely possible that the 8 billionth time that something happens that supposedly &quot;causes&quot; something the &quot;effect&quot; may not take place. There is no rationally compelling argument to require events that have collocated in space and time in the past to do so in the future. However the argument from experience is more than adequate to essentially require this assumption to be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> de rigeur</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for everyone.<br>
<br>
